{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568795"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:22:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:22:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21387"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21387"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.69,0.19,0.03,0.08,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14260"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101140"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14260","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14260"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21387"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83574"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2015"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"9971"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12798"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"34801"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43749"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44444"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101140"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman who is 30 weeks pregnant presents to her general practitioner with a three-day history of fever, myalgia, and productive cough. Rapid antigen testing confirms influenza A infection. Her oxygen saturation is 94% on room air.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHistorically, pregnant women have experienced more severe disease and higher mortality rates during influenza pandemics compared to non-pregnant women of similar age.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best explains why pregnant women are more susceptible to severe influenza infection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Suppression of cell-mediated immunity","Reduced functional residual capacity","Increased cardiac output during pregnancy","Increased metabolic demands of the fetus","Elevated progesterone levels"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary reason pregnant women experience more severe influenza infection is \u003Cstrong\u003Esuppression of cell-mediated immunity\u003C/strong\u003E. During pregnancy, the maternal immune system undergoes modifications to prevent rejection of the fetus, which contains paternal antigens that would otherwise be recognized as foreign. This immunological adaptation includes downregulation of T-cell activity and other components of cell-mediated immunity, which are crucial for fighting viral infections like influenza.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased cardiac output during pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E - While cardiac output increases during pregnancy to meet the demands of the growing fetus, this cardiovascular adaptation does not directly increase susceptibility to viral infections.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElevated progesterone levels\u003C/strong\u003E - Although progesterone has some immunomodulatory effects, it is not the primary mechanism responsible for increased influenza severity.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced functional residual capacity\u003C/strong\u003E - The growing uterus elevates the diaphragm, reducing lung volumes. While this may contribute to respiratory complications once infection is established, it does not explain the initial increased susceptibility to viral infection.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased metabolic demands of the fetus\u003C/strong\u003E - Higher metabolic demands may reduce maternal reserves to cope with illness but do not directly affect immune response to viral infection.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe suppression of cell-mediated immunity during pregnancy has been consistently observed to increase susceptibility to viral infections, particularly influenza. This explains why pregnant women have experienced higher morbidity and mortality during all major influenza pandemics, including the 2009 H1N1 pandemic.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pregnant women experience physiological suppression of cell-mediated immunity to prevent rejection of the fetus.","Reduced cell-mediated immunity during pregnancy increases susceptibility to viral infections, particularly influenza.","Pregnant women have higher morbidity and mortality rates during influenza pandemics compared to non-pregnant women."],"references":["Nelson-Piercy C. Handbook of obstetric medicine. 6th ed. Boca Raton: CRC Press; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83574"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21387"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83574"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-30T13:08:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-30T13:09:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14260"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101140"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u